---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import TierTable from "../components/TierTable.astro";
import CodeBlock from "../components/CodeBlock.astro";
import CtaButton from "../components/CtaButton.astro";

const pythonExample = `# Not on PyPI yet — install from source (registry publish coming soon):
#   pip install "git+https://github.com/orogen-network/customer-sdk-py"
from orogen_sdk import OrogenClient

# base_url defaults to the live test-mode gateway when omitted.
with OrogenClient(
    api_key="orog_...",
    base_url="https://gateway.orogen.network/v1",
) as client:
    response = client.chat.completions.create(
        model="llama-3.1-70b-instruct@my-finetune-v3",   # base@adapter syntax
        messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Summarise this contract clause..."}],
        useful_tier="dc-standard",      # dc-premium | dc-standard | cloud-rented | prosumer | edge | embed-only
        max_tokens=512,
        useful_verify_receipt=True,     # client-side, best-effort receipt check
    )

    print(response.choices[0]["message"]["content"])
    # Receipt + verification summary travel with every response.
    print(response.useful_verification.overall)`;

const typescriptExample = `// Not on npm yet — install from source (registry publish coming soon):
//   npm install github:orogen-network/customer-sdk-ts
import { OrogenClient } from "@orogen/sdk";

const client = new OrogenClient({
  apiKey: process.env.OROGEN_API_KEY!,
  // baseUrl defaults to https://gateway.orogen.network/v1 when omitted.
  baseUrl: "https://gateway.orogen.network/v1",
});

const response = await client.chat.completions.create({
  model: "llama-3.1-70b-instruct@my-finetune-v3",
  messages: [{ role: "user", content: "Summarise this contract clause..." }],
  useful_tier: "dc-standard",
  max_tokens: 512,
  useful_verify_receipt: true,
});

console.log(response.choices[0]?.message.content);
console.log(response.useful_verification);`;

const litellmExample = `# Not on PyPI yet — install from source (coming soon):
#   pip install "git+https://github.com/orogen-network/litellm-backend-driver"
import litellm

response = litellm.completion(
    model="orogen/llama-3.1-70b-instruct@my-finetune-v3",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Hello"}],
    api_base="https://gateway.orogen.network/v1",
    api_key="orog_...",
)`;

const openaiCompat = `# Use the OpenAI SDK as-is — the gateway is OpenAI-compatible.
# You lose tier selection + receipt verification, but the request works.
from openai import OpenAI

client = OpenAI(
    api_key="orog_...",
    base_url="https://gateway.orogen.network/v1",
)

response = client.chat.completions.create(
    model="llama-3.1-70b-instruct",
    messages=[{"role": "user", "content": "Hello"}],
)`;

const verifyReceipt = `# Verifying a receipt independently with the SDK helper.
from orogen_sdk import verify_receipt

# response.useful_receipt is the RFC-0001 record returned with every response.
result = verify_receipt(response.useful_receipt, expected_nonce=nonce)
# result fields: signature_valid, attestation_fresh, nonce_unique,
#                model_in_registry, overall
assert result.overall, "receipt failed client-side verification"`;
---

<Base
  title="Customers"
  description="Orogen is a drop-in OpenAI-compatible inference network. Per-tier pricing, signed receipts, Python and TypeScript SDKs, LiteLLM provider, and chain-anchored audit trail."
  path="/customers"
>
  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">For customers</p>
    <h1 class="mt-2 text-4xl font-semibold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
      Drop-in OpenAI compatibility. Receipt-grade verifiability.
    </h1>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      Point your existing OpenAI client at the live Forge gateway
      (<code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5 text-magma-300">https://gateway.orogen.network/v1</code>)
      and your code works unchanged. The difference shows up in two places: you
      can pick a hardware tier per request, and every response comes back with a
      receipt that you can verify locally against the chain. The gateway is in
      <strong class="text-crust-100">test mode</strong> on Forge — see the
      <a class="text-magma-300 underline" href="https://docs.orogen.network/start/forge-testnet">testnet caveats</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">Pricing</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Pay per tier. Pay per 1M tokens.</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        Base price posture: <strong class="text-crust-100">~$0.40 per 1M output tokens</strong>
        for Llama-3.1-70B FP8 at the dc-standard tier (0.6× base). The base price
        is set by the gateway as a smoothed function of operator costs and
        verification overhead; per-tier multipliers stack on top.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-8">
        <TierTable variant="customer" />
      </div>

      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-5 lg:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-crust-100">Volume discounts</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-crust-300">
            Large customers (5B+ tokens/month) negotiate sub-base rates with the
            foundation directly. The protocol burn is still settled at the
            gateway; the discount is taken from the gross-price spread.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-crust-100">KV-warm continuations</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-crust-300">
            Session-pinned multi-turn calls land back on the same operator with
            warm KV; operator can offer ~10–20% off marginal-turn pricing for
            in-session continuations.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="surface-card">
          <h3 class="text-sm font-semibold text-crust-100">No subscription floor</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-crust-300">
            Pay-as-you-go from the first token. CUC credits are USD-pegged and
            expire 30 days after mint — top up only what you'll use.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Python SDK</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">orogen-sdk</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      The Python SDK wraps the OpenAI client, adds tier selection, and exposes
      the receipt object. Not on PyPI yet (coming soon) — install from source:
      <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5 text-magma-300">pip install "git+https://github.com/orogen-network/customer-sdk-py"</code>.
    </p>
    <CodeBlock code={pythonExample} lang="python" filename="example.py" />
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">TypeScript SDK</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">@orogen/sdk</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        The TypeScript SDK is a thin layer over <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5 text-magma-300">fetch</code>
        with first-class types for tiers and receipts. Not on npm yet (coming
        soon) — install from source:
        <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5 text-magma-300">npm install github:orogen-network/customer-sdk-ts</code>.
      </p>
      <CodeBlock code={typescriptExample} lang="typescript" filename="example.ts" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">LiteLLM provider</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">litellm-orogen-provider</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      If you're already using LiteLLM for multi-provider routing, the Orogen
      provider drops in alongside OpenAI, Anthropic, Together, etc.
    </p>
    <CodeBlock code={litellmExample} lang="python" filename="litellm-example.py" />
  </section>

  <section class="border-y border-crust-800/80 bg-crust-900/40 py-16">
    <div class="container-page">
      <p class="heading-eyebrow">OpenAI SDK compatibility</p>
      <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">No new SDK required.</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
        The gateway implements <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5 text-magma-300">/v1/chat/completions</code>,
        <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5 text-magma-300">/v1/completions</code>,
        <code class="rounded bg-crust-800 px-1 py-0.5 text-magma-300">/v1/embeddings</code>, and SSE streaming. You can use the
        OpenAI SDK with no changes — you lose tier selection and receipt
        verification, but every other request type works identically.
      </p>
      <CodeBlock code={openaiCompat} lang="python" filename="openai-compat.py" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container-page py-16">
    <p class="heading-eyebrow">Receipt verification</p>
    <h2 class="mt-2 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Trust, but verify locally.</h2>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      Every response carries a receipt with the operator signature, the
      attestation quote chain (NVTrust + Intel TA / AMD KDS), and the content
      hashes. The customer SDK verifies the signature locally and (optionally)
      verifies the attestation chain against root certificates of record. The
      chain stores the receipt commitment for arbitration if you ever need to
      escalate a dispute.
    </p>
    <CodeBlock code={verifyReceipt} lang="python" filename="verify.py" />

    <p class="mt-6 max-w-3xl text-crust-300">
      Note on verifiability claims. The verification stack is <em>cryptographic
      at the receipt level</em> (you can prove a given operator returned a given
      output for a given input) and <em>statistical at the network level</em>
      (validator replay sampling targets 1–5% of jobs at dc-standard, more at
      lower tiers). Strong per-query verifiability requires the zkML option
      (L6), which is currently economical only for very high-stakes workloads.
      See the FAQ for the trade-offs.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
      <CtaButton href="/downloads" variant="primary">Download SDKs</CtaButton>
      <CtaButton href="https://docs.orogen.network" variant="secondary" rel="noopener noreferrer">API reference</CtaButton>
      <CtaButton href="/faq" variant="ghost">FAQ</CtaButton>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
